Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:28.440 --> 00:33.800
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

00:36.420 --> 00:38.140
And here are your hosts.

00:42.180 --> 00:49.480
This is David Carson and Daryl Lane. Theodore Sturgeon is one of the finest
writers science fiction and fantasy has ever produced. For 45 years, Sturgeon

00:49.480 --> 00:56.240
has created imaginative fiction that is noted for its innovative themes and
perfection of style. A large percentage of his works have become classics in the

00:56.240 --> 01:03.540
field. His novel More Than Human, for example, are the powerful short story
"Thunder and Roses". We spoke with Sturgeon recently and asked him to tell us how

01:03.540 --> 01:15.520
he became a writer. I began to write when I was an able seaman in the Merchant
Marine. And how that came about was that I left home before I graduated from

01:15.520 --> 01:26.340
high school. It's a fascinating thing. I lecture at colleges and universities
all over the United States and in England and in France. And I have yet to get

01:26.340 --> 01:37.240
my high school diploma. Someday somebody will grant me an honorary high school
diploma. But anyway, I was on the ships and you had a lot of time to read. And I

01:37.240 --> 01:46.820
conceived the idea of an absolutely foolproof crime that would net me thousands
and thousands of dollars. And I even did research on it. I was on a coastwise

01:46.820 --> 01:55.940
tanker. And as I was going up and down the coast, when we'd stop at a port, I
would send off a letter to the railroad. So it was one of the things that was

01:55.940 --> 02:02.580
involved. And the insurance companies, that was another, and the post office,
that was still another. I got all my research done as to how to commit this

02:02.580 --> 02:14.740
particular kind of robbery. And, you know, they had letters carefully written so
that nobody would know what I was up to. And when I had all my material, I found

02:14.740 --> 02:27.900
that I did not have the immoral courage to commit the crime. So I wrote it as a
story. This was way back in the late 30s. And I sent my story off to a newspaper

02:27.900 --> 02:37.560
syndicate. I didn't know anything about writing particularly. And they were
buying 1,500-word short short stories that they published every day in the

02:37.560 --> 02:51.660
syndicate. And when I got up to New York in the ship, to my amazement, I got a
letter of acceptance. And so I quit the sea and came ashore to be a writer. And

02:51.660 --> 03:02.520
I got my money not on acceptance but on publication. And it was five whole
dollars. And they would buy one and sometimes two stories a week but no more.

03:03.100 --> 03:13.200
And so four and a half months or so, I lived on five and sometimes ten dollars a
week. My room cost me seven. And whatever I saved, I could eat. And I learned a

03:13.200 --> 03:26.260
lot about being hungry. Did you ever notice that pound cake has no crust on the
ends? What they do is chop them off and they sell them in their day-old store.

03:26.720 --> 03:35.540
And at that time, you could get a whole shopping bag full of cake ends for a
nickel. And so I used to live on that. One time, I got a whole shopping bag full

03:35.540 --> 03:44.060
and it was moldy but I ate it anyhow. And I was so sick, I didn't eat for three
days. And so I saved myself some money. You know, I was like that. It was a hard

03:44.060 --> 03:45.320
school. It really was.

04:01.120 --> 04:07.980
Sturgeon persisted as a writer, though, earning his living writing pulp fiction.
And pulp fiction, we should add, that surpassed almost anything else coming out

04:07.980 --> 04:18.660
in the pulp format. Then Sturgeon met someone who gave his career a big boost.
Then I finally, after some months of that, and I think I went back to sea for a

04:18.660 --> 04:31.780
short while, I finally met John Campbell in 1939, early 1939. He was the editor
of Astounding Science Fiction and a wonderful fantasy magazine called Unknown.

04:34.440 --> 04:42.880
And so I started writing for him. And then after that, it just exploded. One
time, I had four stories on the stands at the same time. In those two magazines,

04:43.040 --> 04:45.440
I had to get two new names.

04:47.580 --> 04:53.720
So it was an interesting beginning. On our next show, we'll continue our
conversation with Theodore Sturgeon.

