Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

06:09.840 --> 06:15.180
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

06:17.820 --> 06:19.520
And here are your hosts.

06:23.440 --> 06:31.020
This is Daryl Lane. And David Carson. Much of Theodore Sturgeon's early science
fiction and fantasy was published in the pulp magazines of the 30s and 40s. Yet

06:31.020 --> 06:38.120
Sturgeon is known as one of the finest stylists science fiction has ever
produced. And the pulps were not exactly a seedbed for perfection of style. When

06:38.120 --> 06:46.440
we spoke with Sturgeon, we observed that he hardly belongs to the pulp category.
Well, you know, this is difficult with the whole matter of categorization.

06:46.660 --> 06:58.880
Anyway, we're in the grip of the taxonomist. And people who put labels on things
and stick them into cubby holes. Taxonomy has its uses. There's no question

06:58.880 --> 07:08.620
about that. You have to be able to find and retrieve information, and that's
what taxonomy is all about. But more and more there seems to come over our whole

07:08.620 --> 07:17.380
culture the idea that if you can put a label on it, you understand it. And that
is not what taxonomy is for. Taxonomy is handles by which you can pick something

07:17.380 --> 07:29.520
up and look at it. But for so many people, in so many ways, the label is
sufficient. You know, he's a Republican, or his mother was a Jew, or, yeah, he,

07:29.820 --> 07:41.360
you know, he's a poet, he's an esbyte, or whatever. They're all labels. And
there's a little effort made to understand what's under these labels. Pulp

07:41.360 --> 07:50.160
fiction has suffered from the same thing. Pulp actually referred to the kind of
paper it was printed on, not to its quality. There was the pulps and there were

07:50.160 --> 07:57.780
the slicks. The slicks were magazines like the Saturday Evening Post and
Collier's. And the Ladies' Home Journal. And the pulps were things like Black

07:57.780 --> 08:08.140
Mask and Air War stories and science fiction and fantasy and the like. But it
was so easy for the taxonomists and for people who don't pay proper attention to

08:08.140 --> 08:19.680
what was going on to feel that pulp was a qualitative comment and slick was also
qualitative. Slick paper was better literature than pulp paper. 

08:19.680 --> 08:26.300
Some of the finest writing around. Some of
the best pulp writers as such. I mean, the best writers of the time began in

08:26.300 --> 08:37.620
pulp. And they only gravitated to the slicks, not because they got better, but
because they got paid more. Ray Bradbury is a perfect example of that. So is

08:37.620 --> 08:46.840
Dashiell Hammett and the like. We asked Sturgeon why he devoted himself to
science fiction and fantasy. Why didn't he write regular or mainstream fiction?

08:47.500 --> 08:57.020
Well, first of all, because I love the field. Because it's the only genre which
has no limitations whatsoever. A lot of people there, the taxonomists, they're

08:57.020 --> 09:05.660
into it again. They feel that science fiction is the literature of the future
and of space, which is nonsense. It's true that a lot of it is, but you can

09:05.660 --> 09:12.660
write science fiction about the past, you can write science fiction about that
marvelous place called Other. Just some Other place that doesn't have any

09:12.660 --> 09:21.780
reference to where we go in the future. That's the best kind. That's the kind
that I think one of the things that science fiction is for. If you don't like

09:21.780 --> 09:30.700
the government, go ahead and create a new kind of government. Give it a push and
see how it works. You can study whole cultures and religions and also some

09:30.700 --> 09:40.740
literature and art. I've gone into that in some of my stories, which are
essentially in places that occur just Other. Not in the future or in the past

09:40.740 --> 09:51.000
necessarily. One of the very finest science fiction books around is by somebody
I'm very proud to call one of my ex-students. It's called Wild Seed. It's by

09:51.000 --> 10:04.360
Octavia Butler. And it begins somewhere around the 17th century and goes up to
about 1910, which is hardly future fiction. It's a totally original structure,

10:04.560 --> 10:14.680
original idea, and beautifully, beautifully written. That lady is tremendous.
She really is. One of the big ones. When Sturgeon began publishing his fiction

10:14.680 --> 10:22.120
back in the late 30s, science fiction had not yet exploded. Most of it was still
published in pulp magazines rather than books. The pulp authors were often

10:22.120 --> 10:29.440
writers who also wrote westerns, adventure fiction, detectives, and so forth.
Sturgeon contributed greatly to the growing popularity of science fiction and

10:29.440 --> 10:33.340
indeed helped usher it into its golden age. We'll talk about such matters on our
next show.

