12:00.960 --> 12:02.660
And here are your hosts.

12:06.700 --> 12:13.640
This is David Carson and Daryl Lane. Theodore Sturgeon has influenced science
fiction as few other writers have. He began publishing science fiction and

12:13.640 --> 12:20.600
fantasy in the late 1930s and quickly became recognized as one of the most
unique stylists and thinkers in the field. We asked him if he associated with

12:20.600 --> 12:30.820
any other writers in those early days. Was there any sense of community or
fellowship among science fiction writers? Oh, sure. I am characteristically not

12:30.820 --> 12:42.860
a joiner as such. There was a group called the Hydra Club, which was completely
informal. And the rule one was that there are no rules for this organization. An

12:42.860 --> 12:52.000
awful lot of people belonged to the Hydra Club. And through that, in the early
years, I got to know all sorts of people like Horace Gold and Fred Pohl and

12:52.000 --> 13:05.340
Henry Kuttner and so on. Well, the whole raft of those early writers, I think I
knew them all. And there was a group there. Fred Pohl has written about them

13:05.340 --> 13:15.460
called the Futurians. I was never involved in that particularly. I attended the
very first Milford Science Fiction Writers Conference in Milford, New Jersey. I

13:15.460 --> 13:28.540
guess that was in 1951. And Judith Merril I was very close to. Well, I knew
virtually everybody in the field at that time, except one or two of the West

13:28.540 --> 13:29.240
Coast people.

13:37.840 --> 13:44.860
Back in the 40s, Sturgeon's style and his innovative themes were startlingly
fresh in a field that was noted for its cliches and formulas. Science fiction

13:44.860 --> 13:52.060
author, critic, and historian James Gunn has written that because of Theodore
Sturgeon, other writers have been freer to write what they wish to write and

13:52.060 --> 14:00.780
were able to find a market for it. We wondered if Sturgeon were conscious of
himself as having that kind of role. Not at all. Not at all. I tell you, the

14:00.780 --> 14:14.180
last few years have been real revelations to me. For one thing, I didn't realize
that I'd had so much personal impact on people. Until, what was it, six years or

14:14.180 --> 14:23.040
so now, I went to Italy. And a woman came up to me dragging an interpreter. And
the interpreter said, she doesn't speak any English, but there are two things

14:23.040 --> 14:31.800
that she wants to tell you. One of them is that you write women better than any
writer she knows. And the other thing is that because of something that you

14:31.800 --> 14:44.380
wrote, she did not kill herself one night. And the woman began to cry, and the
interpreter began to cry, and I began to cry. And it was quite an experience. I

14:44.380 --> 14:53.780
suddenly realized that what I have done, apparently, I've been able to reach a
great many people far deeper than I had any idea that I was doing. When I look

14:53.780 --> 15:03.140
back over the mail that I've gotten over the years, I realized how many people
in how many different ways have told me that same kind of thing. It's extremely

15:03.140 --> 15:14.820
gratifying. It's also a little frightening. I mean, it's frightening enough to
make you terrified of touching your typewriter. Barry Malzberg, another author

15:14.820 --> 15:22.280
and critic of science fiction, has called Sturgeon the most important science
fiction writer of the 40s. Malzberg says that because of Sturgeon's style, his

15:22.280 --> 15:28.940
internalization or use of psychology, and his quirky characters, he opened the
door for everything that happened in the 50s. Sturgeon read Malzberg's

15:28.940 --> 15:39.080
assessment. His response is interesting. Yeah, I'll tell you quickly a story. A
few years ago, there was a little boy who went to see his buddy. He was 67 years

15:39.080 --> 15:47.140
old. His mother told him to be back before dark. And he was so busy playing with
his friend that he looked out the window and saw it was dark. And he went

15:47.140 --> 15:56.180
rushing home. And like little kids will, he dragged a stick along a picket
fence. And when he got to the corner, he whanged it against the lamppost. And

15:56.180 --> 16:05.100
immediately, all the lights in the northeastern United States went out. Remember
that one, that big blackout? He went rushing home to his mother, weeping, and

16:05.100 --> 16:14.860
threw himself into her arms. And said, God, Mommy, I didn't mean it. I didn't
mean it. Well, this is the way I felt when I first read things like this. More

16:14.860 --> 16:16.140
with Theodore Sturgeon next time.

16:23.240 --> 16:31.000
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

16:31.000 --> 16:31.760
Odessa, Texas.

