17:42.940 --> 17:44.680
And here are your hosts.

17:48.660 --> 17:55.920
This is Daryl Lane. And David Carson. Theodore Sturgeon is known as one of the
finest short story writers who has ever written science fiction and fantasy. But

17:55.920 --> 18:03.640
he's also published novels. One of them, More Than Human, is a genuine science
fiction classic. It came out in 1953 and won the International Fantasy Award in

18:03.640 --> 18:11.560
1954. More Than Human is really three interconnected stories dealing with
extrasensory powers. It depicts, in Sturgeon's impressionistic style, the coming

18:11.560 --> 18:19.360
together of six freaks, children who have latent psy-powers but who are lost and
ineffectual when they are alone. But as a group, a gestalt that functions as a

18:19.360 --> 18:27.800
single organism, they succeed and become symbolic of a new level of human
maturity. Sturgeon talks about More Than Human. The springboard for that was in

18:27.800 --> 18:36.740
a book by Pearl Buck, which was called Pavilion of Women. I read it so many
years ago that I hardly remember the book at all. But there was one passage in

18:36.740 --> 18:45.660
there which described a monk who took care of some children in a cave in the
woods. And they were uneducated and wild children. They'd have died without him.

18:46.160 --> 18:57.700
And he was just an impoverished monk himself. And he took care of these raggedy
little children. And that image always stayed with me. And somehow that and the

18:57.700 --> 19:10.620
whole idea of what would happen if each of these children, coming from various
places and being various kinds of children, had very special ESP talents. And

19:10.620 --> 19:23.660
again, it was a question of investigating what the impact would be on the world
as a whole as some of the newly recognized proclivities of the human mind came

19:23.660 --> 19:32.020
up. And this, of course, there are literally thousands of books that have been
written on that theme since then. Sturgeon says the book has been his most

19:32.020 --> 19:43.480
popular among readers. When I sold Finnish and Israeli rights two years ago, it
got into its 15th and 16th languages. And just how many editions, I have no idea

19:43.480 --> 19:53.740
genuinely. I know there are five or six English editions and several Spanish and
a number of French and four Japanese editions. And I think I'm proudest of all

19:53.740 --> 20:03.500
of that. If a novel can pass the language barrier and the cultural barrier and
go into more editions, then I think that's a real achievement.

20:10.400 --> 20:18.740
Another Sturgeon novel is Venus Plus X, a book strong on ideas. And the main
idea is sexual stereotyping in our society, the seemingly predetermined roles

20:18.740 --> 20:28.080
men and women must take on. Sturgeon talks about the impetus behind Venus Plus
X. That came about by I was leafing through a magazine, and I saw an ad for, of

20:28.080 --> 20:40.520
all things, tire chains. Weed tire chains. And there was a photograph of a girl
in her underwear holding out a tire chain. And it stopped me cold. I thought,

20:40.740 --> 20:51.860
what on earth has that got to do with a tire chain? Clearly, you know, it was a
grabber by the advertising business. Makes you stop and look at the ad. But what

20:51.860 --> 21:01.080
has a girl without clothes got to do with a tire chain? And I began to
think, what kind of a civilization, what would it be like to live in a culture

21:01.080 --> 21:13.300
where there was no particular sexual bias at all? And so I started, first of
all, creating a society in which there was no sexual at all, that people were,

21:13.440 --> 21:24.440
they generated like oysters, which can be both either male or female. But at the
beginning, they're neither. And I couldn't make that work. So I went in another

21:24.440 --> 21:30.220
direction and created a race of people. And each individual was both sexes.

21:33.120 --> 21:43.860
And therefore, there was no sexual differentiation. They were just people. And
it got into their love and marriage, their sexuality, also into their art, their

21:43.860 --> 21:55.080
literature, their architecture, and so on. I had a ball with that. Venus Plus X
is not, you know, really a novel at all. It's a tract. It's an exposition of

21:55.080 --> 21:59.940
the ideas that I was getting at the time. We'll continue our conversation with
Theodore Sturgeon next time.

